Articles.Content:
I've been trying to play KSP via Steam after the latest beta update with some very bad results. Currently, I'm running OS X 10.9.5 on a hackintosh, i7 2600k, 8GB RAM, Radeon 6870 1GB. No other games have issues, and I've run some recently that are definitely more taxing on the hardware than KSP. I also ran memtest via a burned ISO with no issues, so I doubt the problem is bad memory.

In past versions I've had problems getting very large craft (as in 1000+ parts) back into the hangar without the endless beachball of doom. Well, now even tiny craft are a total crap shoot! If I try to revert to the hangar, I'll get the black screen with the loading icon in the lower right. It won't move, nothing happens, no sound, and the beachball of doom appears. Unfortunately, I did not grab the Player.log for one of these, but I do recall that it had to do with a failed malloc and an unhandled NULL exception with 256 frames captured, and all past the first few were something to the effect of mono_traverse_object.

The latest issue involved a much larger craft. I didn't even make it to the launch pad. I finished up, clicked "Launch", waited a sec, and got most of the UI, the static screens for the three kerbal pilots, and a giant rainbow on the rest of the screen. It froze there and I had to force quit. I do have the Player.log from that one, added below.

The malloc failures seem to be a common thread. I would think it has to do with running out of memory, but I've had well over 4GB free opening it up on both occasions. If it's a memory problem, then KSP seems to have trouble fitting into a 32-bit memory space.

I'm using no mods, nothing extra. I've tried repairing the game cache, deleting the save state, and setting the permissions on the game folder. No dice. This has been getting worse with every major update.

Hi SomeoneElse, I'm no OSX guy but I'm pretty sure if you're seeing breakpoints and malloc errors then you've got a serious problem, possibly hardware or the OS itself.

Can you give us more information on your system please.

i7 2600k, 8GB DDR3 1600, 1TB hard drive + 120GB SSD in a Fusion Drive, Radeon 6870 1GB, Gigabyte Z68XP-UD3P motherboard.

It's a hackintosh running OS 10.9.5, UEFI boot, no DSDT, minimal supporting kexts and not much more than that.

As I said, I've had no problems with other games and applications that tax the hardware more than KSP does. A recent Memtest run didn't find any problems with the RAM. Other threads seem to indicate that it's an issue with KSP (especially on OS X) not being able to fit into a 32-bit memory space. The recommendation was either lowering texture resolution or using a third party texture compression mod. I did the latter, which may have helped, but then I got the crash on the stack decoupler.

You shouldn't need texture compression on an unmodded install unless you're running a lot of other programs that are using your RAM, I did hear of a stack decoupler crash recently though and I was able to reproduce it with the craft file provided, but only with that craft.

Are you having an issue with all craft or just some? What about on a new save?

Yeah, I found the thread where the other guy was having issues. I also found an older thread with a fix for the same issue several versions ago. I tried the workaround (set PhysicsSignificance = 0 in the part.cfg file) and it worked on the next try, but that could be a fluke as it is intermittent.

And I've seen these crashes when I have well over 4GB of free RAM upon starting KSP. Apparently Yosemite is even worse, topping out 32-bit applications around 3.1GB or so instead of 3.5GB. I've seen other complaints about this on OS X in the 0.90 beta, and as I mentioned before, I've seen these issues in prior version, although it was generally on gigantic craft, but now I've seen it on smaller ones. The texture compression mod does seem to help, though. After launching a moderately-sized craft and returning to the hangar, it's sitting at about 2.4GB. Hopefully it sticks well enough until the underlying issue of memory management can be addressed.

Well, nope, still locked up trying to get to the launchpad with a fairly large craft. I was able to see the Time Warp 1x text this time, but it never got away from a black screen with the loading indicator otherwise. KSP was eating about 2.89GB at the time, so it wasn't hitting the 32-bit limit. While free memory was essentially gone, there was still gobs of inactive memory left that should have been reallocated as needed. Latest player.log posted.

KSP must be doing something pretty low-level that perhaps it shouldn't. Any other application I've used won't lock up hard when it runs out of free memory. OS X should open up blocks of the inactive memory if possible, free up space by compressing the contents of memory where possible, or even utilize the swap file when that sort of thing happens. KSP seems to be bypassing a number of OS X memory management features, and considering how RAM-hungry it is, perhaps it shouldn't be. Steam must be running when KSP is open for many people. That eats RAM. Telling users that they shouldn't have any other applications open when running KSP or to install over 8GB of RAM in their machines to run it should not be the way it works. Heck, even if you don't have any other applications open, there are usually large chunks of inactive memory in OS X regardless if a number of other applications have recently been run. KSP should be doing a better job of memory management and should integrate better with the host OS to deal with situations like this.

And again, this time with KSP eating nearly 3GB of RAM with around 600MB free. I'd been working on a pretty big ship (800 or so parts) and bungled a placement. I had some fuel tanks set radially around another, 8x, with a few extra parts on them (atomic boosters on bottom, monopropellant tanks/thrusters, radial decouplers with solid fuel boosters). I hit command-Z to undo, and instead of undoing anything, it simply deleted the radial fuel tanks and everything on them! Furthermore, it somehow autoexpanded every part in the staging area and wouldn't let me place new parts. The only thing I did after the tanks disappeared was delete a single fuel line that had inexplicably been left and extended from the central tank to where the now-deleted tanks were. I could click on a part in the palette, but it wouldn't appear in the builder. Frustrated, I tried loading a recent save. That's where it hung on the black screen with the loading icon, and this time it definitely wasn't due to not having enough RAM. I've abridged the player log due to about fifty billion instances of a single error.

At this point, the game is essentially unplayable. I can get a few successful launches, but the frustration of dealing with crashes and lockups simply isn't worth it. I'm glad it's finally in beta, because a lot of this has been accumulating over time without getting fixed. Maybe now the devs can focus on bugstomping and refactoring to clean some of this up.
